<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/10789286-elizabeth-klein"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1344559930i/10789286._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/10789286-elizabeth-klein">Elizabeth Klein</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    It's not really a spoiler but I marked it as such.<br /><br />I really like Kingsolver but I think this is my favorite by far. The characters are much more lovabl<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    It's not really a spoiler but I marked it as such.<br /><br />I really like Kingsolver but I think this is my favorite by far. The characters are much more lovable than The Poisonwood Bible, which is educational but has irritating characters in it.<br /><br /> <br /><br />Taylor and Turtle are the main attraction but many of the characters are lovable, quirky and interesting. You can't help but want them to stay around. I read this book twice because I just loved the characters in it. They are so defined that you can't help but cheer them on. Even the antagonist makes you want to sympathize a bit.<br /><br />I agree that this book also had details that made you learn about Native American history/philosophy and culture. This may seem corny but this novel shows me that family is what you make it. I read it twice. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
